We know that $\log_{10} A + \log_{10} B = \log_{10} AB$. Thus, we have
\begin{align*}
\log_{10} (AL) + \log_{10} (AM) &= 2 \quad &\text{(1)} \\
\log_{10} (A^2LM) &= 2 \quad &\text{(2)} \\
A^2LM &= 10^2 = 100 \quad &\text{(3)}
\end{align*}

Similarly, we get
\begin{align*}
\log_{10} (ML) + \log_{10} (MR) &= 3 \quad &\text{(4)} \\
\log_{10} (LM^2R) &= 3 \quad &\text{(5)} \\
LM^2R &= 10^3 = 1000 \quad &\text{(6)}
\end{align*}

And
\begin{align*}
\log_{10} (RA) + \log_{10} (RL) &= 4 \quad &\text{(7)} \\
\log_{10} (R^2AL) &= 4 \quad &\text{(8)} \\
R^2AL &= 10^4 = 10000 \quad &\text{(9)}
\end{align*}

Multiplying the three equations (3), (6), and (9), we get
\begin{align*}
A^2LM \cdot LM^2R \cdot R^2AL &= 100 \cdot 1000 \cdot 10000 \\
A^3R^3M^3L^3 &= 1000000000 \\
\Rightarrow (ARML)^3 &= 10^9
\end{align*}

Taking the cubic root of both sides, we get
\[ ARML = 10^3 = 1000 \]

The answer is:
\[ \boxed{1000} \]

