We can write each term as a difference of fractions:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2\cdot 3} &= \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3}\\
\frac{1}{3\cdot 4} &= \frac{1}{3} - \frac{1}{4}\\
\frac{1}{4\cdot 5} &= \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{5}\\
&\vdots\\
\frac{1}{11\cdot 12} &= \frac{1}{11} - \frac{1}{12}
\end{align*}

Adding all these equations together, we see that all terms cancel except for the first and last:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2\cdot 3} + \frac{1}{3\cdot 4} + \frac{1}{4\cdot 5} + \dots + \frac{1}{11\cdot 12} &= \left(\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{3} - \frac{1}{4}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{5}\right) + \dots + \left(\frac{1}{11} - \frac{1}{12}\right)\\
&= \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{12}\\
&= \frac{5}{12}
\end{align*}

So, the answer is:
\[ \boxed{\frac{5}{12}} \]

